<br>
I've been hearing for a long time from advocates of the idea that Orion is too old fashioned and other developments make its brute-force approach obsolete.<br>
I've been saying all along that it's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>simple</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->; that even the requirement for greater definition of our models of plasma stagnation and energy coupling and ablation are simpler than the breakthroughs required for another type of drive, and that any leads towards these breakthroughs makes Orion's bombs even better (I'll bet money right now that a grease-mist sprayer is easier!).<br>
<br>
Even though we need better modeling and maybe even some underground and/or in-space nuclear testing with pusher plate models doesn't mean that we have no good reason to doubt that they knew what they were talking about when they said that there are no technical show stoppers at the interface between plasma &amp; solid matter at the surface of the plate.<br>
 For instance, Freeman Dyson said that &quot;nature is on the side of Orion&quot; in allowing different ways of adjusting the opacity and energy transfers to make it work, and Taylor said that there are many known ways to tinker the trigger and plasma to get the balance of KE transfer and heat transfer to do it.<br>
Yes a pusher plate and shock absorbers are heavy, but thay are simple dumb steel to allow ridiculously good performance, compared to everything complex needed for the other proposals; ICAN, Daedalus, GCNR, NSWR, or even VASIMR -and many of these haven't been developed well enough to say that we can expect (anywhere near) the performance and economy of Orion). <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 6/2/03 5:25:52 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 223<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/3/03 4:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=330.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Antiproton assisted... (triggers for Orion bombs)</span><hr size=1> The annhilation of 1 kilogram of anti-protons with<br>
